An '''esbat''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|ˈ|ɛ|s|b|æ|t}}) is a [[coven]] meeting of other than one the [[Sabbats]]<ref name="Farrar">{{cite book|last=Farrar|first=Janet and Stewart|title=The Witches' Way: Principles, Rituals and Beliefs of Modern Witchcraft|year=1984|isbn=0-919345-71-9|pages=320}}</ref> within [[Wicca]] and other Wiccan-influenced forms of [[contemporary Paganism]]. [[Janet Farrar|Janet]] and [[Stewart Farrar]] describe esbats as an opportunity for a "love feast, healing work, psychic training and all."<ref>Farrar, 1984, p. 178.</ref>
==Etymology== The term ''esbat'' is derived from [[Old French]] ''s'esbattre'' (Modern French ''ébat''), meaning ''to frolic and amuse oneself'', ''diversion''.<ref name=dictionary.com>{{cite web|title=Esbat|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/esbat|publisher=Dictionary.com. Random House, Inc.|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=brill>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Contemporary Paganism|year=2009|publisher=[[Brill Publishers]]|location=[[Leiden]], [[Netherlands]]|isbn=978-90-04-16373-7|coauthors=Murphy Pizza, James R. Lewis|page=64|chapter=The Modern Magical Revival: Nevill Drury}}</ref> It was a borrowing by 20th century anthropologist [[Margaret Murray]]'s use of [[European witch trials|French witch trial]] sources on supposed [[Witches' Sabbath]]s in her atempts to "reconstruct" a ''Witch Cult in Western Europe''.
==Observance== An esbat is commonly understood to be a ritual observance on the night of a [[full moon]].<ref name="about.com">{{cite web|last=Wigington|first=Patti|title=Esbat|url=http://paganwiccan.about.com/od/glossary/g/Esbat.htm|work=Paganism / Wicca|publisher=About.com Guide|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> However, the late high priestess [[Doreen Valiente]] distinguished between "full moon Esbat[s]" and other esbatic occasions.<ref name="valiente_rw">{{citation|last=Valiente|first=Doreen|title=The Rebirth of Witchcraft|year=1989|page=123}}</ref>
The term ''esbat'' in this sense was described by [[Margaret Murray]].<ref name=witch_cult>{{citation|last=Murray|first=Margaret|title=Witch Cult in Western Europe: A Study in Anthropology|year=1921 (2003 reprint)|publisher=Sampson Law, Marston & Co., Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7661-4455-2|pages=112 - 123}}</ref><ref name=murray_gw>{{citation|last=Murray|first=Margaret|title=The God of the Witches|year=1933|publisher=Sampson Law, Marston & Co., Ltd.}}</ref> {{Quote|The Esbat differed from the Sabbat by being primarily for business. ... very often the Esbat was for sheer enjoyment only|Murray|1921}}
